  "body": " Work in groups     Draw a table similar to the one shown in below.     For each object in the list, follow the steps below to record its mass in all six units using the applet in Figure .   Conversion of Mass      Select one object from the checklist in the upper left of the applet.     Drag the slider to each of the following units in order. After selecting each unit, record the mass displayed for the object in your table:  Ounces  Pounds  Tons  Milligrams  Grams  Kilograms      De-select the desired object by clicking on it again.     Select the next object and repeat steps until all objects in the checklist have been measured and recorded in .     After completing the table, answer the following questions based on your measurements:     How many grams are in one kilogram? Use values from your table to support your answer.    How many ounces are in one pound?    Which object had the smallest mass in milligrams? How did its value compare in ounces?    Describe one interesting pattern or relationship you observed when converting an object's mass through all six units.       Discuss and share your findings with the rest of the class.      Conversion Units of Mass    Object  mass (ounces)  mass (pounds)  mass (tons)  mass (milligrams)  mass (grams)  mass (kilograms)    Pencil           cellphone           potatoes           milk jug           microwave           socks           pillow            "
